lecular mass extends the same carbon‑12 ratio concept from atoms to molecules\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Relative molecular mass is described as a dimensionless quantity that expresses how many times a molecule’s mass is greater than 1/12 of the mass of a carbon‑12 atom. This parallels the definition of relative atomic mass but applies it at the molecular scale, ensuring conceptual continuity across levels of chemical structure. [Data: Entities (1162); Relationships (1571)]\\n\\nThe entity description states that relative molecular mass is calculated as the sum of the relative atomic masses of all atoms in a molecule’s formula. This provides a simple computational rule that directly ties the molecular-scale quantity to atomic-scale inputs. [Data: Entities (1162)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Molecular formula is the representational input that enables relative molecular mass calculation\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Molecular formula is presented as the atom-by-atom representation of a molecule (e.g., H2O, CO2, C6H12O6) and is specifically linked to the ability to calculate relative molecular mass. Knowing the formula provides the structure needed to sum the relative atomic masses of constituent atoms. [Data: Entities (1177); Relationships (1607)]\\n\\nThe explicit relationship states that if the molecular formula is known, relative molecular mass can be calculated by summing relative atomic masses, highlighting a clear dependency chain: formula → atomic composition → summed relative atomic masses → relative molecular mass. [Data: Relationships (1607); Entities (1162, 1161, 1177)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"The Avogadro constant connects carbon‑12, particle counting, and the mole\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The Avogadro constant is defined as the number of atoms in 12.00 g of carbon‑12 and given a value of 6.022 × 10^23, representing the number of basic entities in one mole. This directly links the carbon‑12 reference mass to macroscopic coun